[[File:Bjoernsholm bugt.jpg|thumb|Bjørnsholm Bay around 1900]]
'''Bjørnsholm Bay''' ({{lang-da|Bjørnsholm Bugt}}) is a bay in the [[Limfjord]], along [[Himmerland]]'s west coast, {{convert|10|-|20|km|mi|0}} southwest of [[Løgstør]], Denmark. The bay is named after the estate of [[Bjørnsholm]] and extends approximately {{convert|9|km|mi}} from the hamlet of [[Rønbjerg]] in the north to the cliffs at [[Ertebølle]] in the south. Near Bjørnsholm and the [[Vitskøl monastery]], Bjørnsholm Å (Bjørnsholm Stream) runs into the bay, and almost four kilometers to the south Trend Å (Trend Stream) has its mouth at [[Trend (city)|Trend]], where there is a cottage area. Nearby in the Limfjord is the island of [[Livø]], whose southeastern tip, Livø Tab, almost reaches the bay.<ref name="pern">{{cite web | title=Stenaldercenter | website=Vesthimmerlands Museum | url=http://www.vesthimmerlandsmuseum.dk/Stenaldercenter | language=da | access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>

