{{about|the form of address|other uses|The Good Wife (disambiguation)}}
{{refimprove|date=November 2010}}
'''Goodwife''' ([[Scots language|Scots]]: ''Guidwife''), usually abbreviated '''Goody''', was a polite form of address for women, formerly used where "Mrs.", "Miss" and "Ms." would be used today. Its male counterpart is [[Goodman (title)|Goodman]]. However, a woman addressed by this title was of a lesser social rank than a woman addressed as [[Mistress (form of address)|Mistress]]. 

"Goodwife" and "Goody" were used in [[England]], [[Scotland]], and [[Colonial history of the United States|Colonial America]], with the earliest known use circa 1325.<ref>"Goodwife", ''Oxford England Dictionary''.</ref> By the mid-18th century they had become [[archaism|archaic]] outside Scotland, and they are perhaps best known today as the forms of address used in [[Arthur Miller]]'s historical fiction ''[[The Crucible]]'', in [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]]'s short story "[[Young Goodman Brown]]", the novels ''[[Magnus (novel)|Magnus]]'' by [[George Mackay Brown]], ''[[The Witch of Blackbird Pond]]'' (name Goodwife Cruff) by [[Elizabeth George Speare]], and [[Mossflower]] by [[Brian Jacques]].

Although the expression "Goody Two-Shoes" is sometimes credited to the children's book ''[[The History of Little Goody Two-Shoes]]'' (1765), the expression appears as far back as a century earlier.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Goody Two-Shoes|journal=American Notes and Queries|volume=5|issue=1|date=May 3, 1890|pages=3}}</ref>

